---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import ReceiverStartup from '@/components/react/startup/ReceiverStartup.tsx';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Cold / warm / hot start"
  description="What an OSNMA receiver does when it powers on after a variable time off."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="5 · The receiver"
    title="Powering on after time off"
    lead="When a receiver wakes up, how much work it must do before it can trust a single bit of navigation data depends on two things: what it kept in memory, and how long it was switched off."
  />

  <p>
    The Receiver Guidelines define three start-up scenarios by what cryptographic
    material is already in non-volatile memory <DocRef doc="rxg" section="4.1.1" />.
    Each one lets the receiver skip part of the chain of trust it would otherwise
    have to rebuild from scratch:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cold start</strong> — only the Merkle root is stored. Everything else must be acquired and verified.</li>
    <li><strong>Warm start</strong> — a previously verified public key is also stored, so the Merkle-tree climb is skipped.</li>
    <li><strong>Hot start</strong> — a verified KROOT and chain parameters are stored too, so the signed DSM-KROOT need not be re-fetched.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    But stored material does not stay valid forever. The longer the receiver was
    off, the more likely a key chain rolled over, a public key was renewed, or —
    very rarely — the whole Merkle tree changed. So a hot start can quietly
    <em>degrade</em> into a warm or cold start. Drag the time slider below and watch
    which steps light up.
  </p>

  <ReceiverStartup client:visible />

  <h2>Reading the flow</h2>
  <p>
    The six stages are the receiver's verification chain, top to bottom. Their
    colours tell you where each piece of trust comes from on this run: green is
    reused from memory, blue is fetched from the live signal, purple is downloaded
    out-of-band from the GSC server, gold is computed, and cyan is the final MAC
    check that authenticates the data.
  </p>

  <h3>Why the time matters so much</h3>
  <p>
    Two firm numbers from the documents drive the cost. A DSM-KROOT must be fully
    received within one hour and a DSM-PKR within thirteen hours, or the partial
    blocks are discarded <DocRef doc="rxg" section="3.2" />. And because the TESLA
    chain advances one key every 30-second subframe, re-anchoring a cached key
    costs exactly one hash per missed subframe <DocRef doc="rxg" section="5.4.2" /> —
    cheap, and proportional to how long you were away, not to the age of the chain.
  </p>

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      A receiver that caches its <em>last verified key</em> (not just the KROOT)
      turns the chain re-anchor into a handful of hashes after a short nap. That is
      the practical difference between a hot start that authenticates within one
      subframe and a cold start that may wait minutes for a fresh DSM-KROOT.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="security">
    <p>
      No matter the scenario, the receiver must first satisfy the time-sync gate:
      its clock uncertainty has to be under 15 seconds for normal tags. Until then,
      a delayed key might already be public and tags could be forged, so no
      authentication is allowed. See
      <a href="/receiver/time-sync">the time synchronisation gate</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
